<div id="aueditable"><!--DO NOT MODIFY THIS LINE AND ABOVE-->

<h1>Bradley&rsquo;s Moral Philosophy</h1><div id="pubinfo"><em>First published Wed Mar 6, 2024</em></div>

<div id="preamble">

<!--pdf exclude begin-->
<p class="smaller">
[<em>Editor&rsquo;s Note: The following entry replaces and includes material from the former entry titled
 <a href="https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/win2023/entries/bradley-moral-political/">Bradley&rsquo; Moral and Political Philosophy</a>.</em>]
</p>
<!--pdf exclude end-->

<p>
F.H. Bradley&rsquo;s moral philosophy remains a source for debates
among the historians of philosophy; its rich&mdash;and
under-researched&mdash;material has much to offer not only to the
history of philosophy but also to contemporary normative ethics and
meta-ethics (especially moral psychology). Luckily, after a period of
neglect, there is a revival of interest in Bradley&rsquo;s ethics. New
attempts are made to reconstruct and reinterpret his ideas, giving
them a well-deserved place within the current debates.</p>

<p>
As a moral philosopher, Bradley is mostly interested in the question
about good personality. The problem of the right action does not have
a central role in his works (even though it is possible to reconstruct
a theory of moral action based on his writings). He asks <em>What sort
of person am I to become</em>? rather than <em>What should I do</em>?
The type of answer that Bradley gives to this question with his theory
of self-realization indicates that he is developing a version of
non-instrumental ethical idealism, according to which the goal of
moral life is the realization of the moral ideal for its own sake.
<em>Ethical Studies</em> is mainly concerned with coming to understand
moral agency and personhood, and this, among other things, entails
laying bare the structure of volitional choice.</p>

<p>
The best source on Bradley&rsquo;s ethics is <em>Ethical Studies</em>,
the philosopher&rsquo;s first major book. The book was first published
in 1876, followed by a second edition with Bradley&rsquo;s comments
for revision in 1927. (All references in this article are to the 1962
paperback edition with R. Wollheim&rsquo;s introduction). Here, he
discusses a wide range of topics relevant to moral philosophy
(including, the freedom of will, justification of morality, moral
duties, obligation). But by far the major contribution of this book is
in moral psychology with its discussion of moral selfhood (cf. Keene
1970), moral ideals, and moral motivation. The book is also valuable
for its critical analysis of the key claims of consequentialism,
hedonism, Kantianism, and Hegelianism. Many classic arguments against
these theories originate from <em>Ethical Studies</em>.</p>

<p>
Bradley&rsquo;s minor works in psychology offer additional insights
into his approach to ethics. As D. Crossley (1989b: 59) notes, these
articles explore in detail concepts and ideas which are only briefly
introduced in the book. Most interesting for ethicists is the reprint
of Bradley&rsquo;s articles titled <em>Collected Essays</em> (1935)
and especially the articles: &ldquo;On Pleasure, Pain, Desire, and
Volition&rdquo; (1888); &ldquo;The Definition of Will
(I&ndash;III)&rdquo; (1902&ndash;04, relevant to the discussion of
motivation, desire, conation, wish, needs, pleasure, and pain);
&ldquo;Some Remarks on Conation&rdquo; (1901, desire and conation);
&ldquo;Can a Man Sin against Knowledge&rdquo; (1884, the nature of
moral judgment); &ldquo;On the Treatment of Sexual Detail in
Literature&rdquo; (desire); &ldquo;On Mental Conflict and
Imputation&rdquo; (1902, desire and personal identity). <em>The
Collected Works of F.H. Bradley</em> (1999) is a treasure trove of
previously unpublished works by Bradley, including moral psychology
and normative ethics: &ldquo;Notes towards <em>Ethical Studies</em>
[c. 1874&ndash;1875]&rdquo; (Vol. I); &ldquo;On Morality [1877 or
1878]&rdquo; (Vol. I); &ldquo;MS BK Z: Chiefly on Psychological Topics
[c. 1893&ndash;1902]&rdquo; (Vol. II); &ldquo;MS BK W: The Final
Commonplace Book [1915&ndash;1924]&rdquo; (Vol. III). Another source
is &ldquo;XXV. Goodness&rdquo; of &ldquo;Appearance and Reality&rdquo;
and it is of primary interest to those who study the evolution of
Bradley&rsquo;s views as well as the way the ethics of later Bradley
fits in the context of his metaphysics.</p>
</div> 

<div id="toc"><!--Entry Contents-->
<ul>
	<li><a href="#BackInfl">1. Background and Influences</a></li>
	<li><a href="#MyStatDuti">2. &ldquo;My Station and Its Duties&rdquo;</a></li>
	<li><a href="#MoraSelfPrecForMoraResp">3. Moral Self as a Precondition for Moral Responsibility</a></li>
	<li><a href="#MoraReleDesi">4. Moral Relevance of Desires</a></li>
	<li><a href="#Inte">5. Integrity</a></li>
	<li><a href="#MoraIdea">6. Moral Ideal</a></li>
	<li><a href="#MoraDeve">7. Moral Development</a></li>
	<li><a href="#LimiMora">8. The Limits of Morality</a></li>
	<li><a href="#Bib">Bibliography</a>
	<ul>
		<li><a href="#PrimLite">Primary Literature</a></li>
