Idealists</em>, Exeter and Charlottesville: Imprint Press,
87&ndash;110.</li>

<li>Krook, Dorothea, 1959, <em>Three Traditions of Moral Thought</em>,
Cambridge:: Cambridge University Press.</li>

<li>MacIntyre, Alasdair C., 1966 [1998], <em>A Short History of
Ethics</em>, (Fields of Philosophy), New York: Macmillan. Second
edition as <em>A Short History of Ethics: A History of Moral
Philosophy from the Homeric Age to the Twentieth Century</em>, London:
Routledge.</li> <!-- second edition has a new preface but the body 
does not seem to have been changed significantly -->

<li>Mackenzie, John S., 1901, <em>A Manual of Ethics</em>, fourth
edition revised and enlarged, New York: Hinds &amp; Noble, and London:
W. B. Clive, University Tutorial Press.</li>

<li>MacEwen, Philip (ed.), 1996, <em>Ethics, Metaphysics and Religion
in the Thought of F. H. Bradley</em>, (Studies in the History of
Philosophy 42), Lewiston, NY: Edwin Mellen Press.</li>

<li>MacNiven, Don, 1984, &ldquo;Bradley&rsquo;s Critiques of
Utilitarian and Kantian Ethics&rdquo;, <em>Idealistic Studies</em>,
14(1): 67&ndash;83. doi:10.5840/idstudies198414114</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1987, <em>Bradley&rsquo;s Moral
Psychology</em>, (Studies in the History of Philosophy 3), Lewiston,
NY: Edwin Mellen Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1996, &ldquo;Metaphysics and Ethics in
Bradley&rsquo;s Idealism&rdquo;, in MacEwen 1996: 91&ndash;109 (ch.
4).</li>

<li>Mander, W. J., 2011, <em>British Idealism: A History</em>,
Oxford/New York: Oxford University Press.
doi:10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199559299.001.0001</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2013, &ldquo;British Idealist
Ethics&rdquo;, in <em>The Oxford Handbook of the History of
Ethics</em>, Roger Crisp (ed.), Oxford: Oxford University Press,
564&ndash;580 (ch. 27).
doi:10.1093/oxfordhb/9780199545971.001.0001</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2016, <em>Idealist Ethics</em>, Oxford:
Oxford University Press.
doi:10.1093/acprof:oso/9780198748892.001.0001</li>

<li>Manser, Anthony Richards and Guy Stock (eds), 1984, <em>The
Philosophy of F.H. Bradley</em>, Oxford: Clarendon Press.</li>

<li>Mill, John Stuart, 1863 [2001], <em>Utilitarianism</em>, London:
Parker, Son &amp; Bourn. Reprinted in 2001, with his 1868 speech on
Capital Punishment, Indianapolis: Hackett Pub.</li>

<li>Milne, A. J. M., 1962, <em>The Social Philosophy of English
Idealism</em>, London: Allen &amp; Unwin.</li>

<li>Muirhead, J.H., 1892, <em>The Elements of Ethics: An Introduction
to Moral Philosophy</em>, London: John Murray.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1932, &ldquo;Francis Herbert
Bradley&rdquo;, in <em>The Great Victorians</em>, H.J. Massingham and
Hugh Massingham (eds), London: Nicholson and Watson, 
33&ndash;46.</li>

<li>Nicholson, Peter P., 1990, <em>The Political Philosophy of the
British Idealists: Selected Studies</em>, Cambridge, New York:
Cambridge University Press.</li>

<li>Norman, Richard, 1983, <em>The Moral Philosophers: An Introduction
to Ethics</em>, Oxford: Clarendon Press.</li>

<li>Pugmire, David, 1996, &ldquo;Some Self: F.H.Bradley on the Self as
&lsquo;Mere&rsquo; Feeling&rdquo;, <em>Bradley Studies</em>, 2(1):
24&ndash;32. doi:10.5840/bradley19962111</li>

<li>Rashdall, Hastings, 1907, <em>The Theory of Good and Evil: A
Treatise on Moral Philosophy</em>, Oxford: The Clarendon Press.</li>

<li>Rescher, Nicholas, 1987, <em>Ethical Idealism: An Inquiry into the
Nature and Function of Ideals</em>, Berkeley: University of
California Press.</li>

<li>Sabine, George H., 1915, &ldquo;The Social Origin of Absolute
Idealism&rdquo;, <em>The Journal of Philosophy, Psychology and
Scientific Methods</em>, 12(7): 169&ndash;177.
doi:10.2307/2013244</li>

<li>Santayana George, 1933, <em>Some Turns of Thought in Modern
Philosophy</em>, London: Cambridge University Press.</li>

<li>Sidgwick, Henry, 1874, <em>The Methods of Ethics</em>, London:
Macmillan.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1876, &ldquo;Review of <em>Ethical
Studies</em>, by F. H. Bradley,&rdquo; <em>Mind</em> (original series), 1(4):
545&ndash;549. doi:10.1093/mind/os-1.4.545</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1954, <em>Outlines of the History of
Ethics</em>, London: Macmillan; first edition, 1886.</li>

<li>Sprigge, T.L.S., 1984, &ldquo;The Self and its World in Bradley
and Husserl&rdquo;, in Manser and Stock 1984: 285&ndash;302.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1988, <em>The Rational Foundations of
Ethics</em>, (The Problems of Philosophy), London/New York: Routledge
&amp; Kegan Paul. doi:10.4324/9781003049333</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1993, <em>James and Bradley: American Truth
and British Reality</em>, La Salle, IL: Open Court.</li>

<li>Stanley, Maurice, 1996, &ldquo;The Paradox of the
Individual&rdquo;, <em>Bradley Studies</em>, 2(1): 51&ndash;63.
doi:10.5840/bradley1996217</li>

<li>Stebbing, Lizzie Susan, 1948, <em>Ideals and Illusions</em>, (The
Thinker&rsquo;s Library 119), London: Watts.</li>

<li>Stern, Robert, 2013, &ldquo;&lsquo;My Station and Its
Duties&rsquo;: Social-Role Accounts of Obligation in Green and
Bradley&rdquo;, in <em>The Impact of Idealism, Volume 1: Philosophy
and Natural Sciences</em>, Karl Ameriks (ed.), Cambridge/New York:
Cambridge University Press, 299&ndash;322.
doi:10.1017/CBO9781139626675.013</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2015, &ldquo;Does Hegelian Ethics Rest on a
Mistake?&rdquo;, in his <em>Kantian Ethics: Value, Agency, and
Obligation</em>, Oxford: Oxford University Press, 157&ndash;170 (ch.
9). Reprinted in <em>&ldquo;I That Is We, We That Is I.&rdquo;
Perspectives on Contemporary Hegel</em>, Italo Testa and Luigi Ruggiu
(eds), Leiden: Brill, 2016, 107&ndash;126 (ch. 6).
doi:10.1163/9789004322967_007</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2017, &ldquo;British Idealism&rdquo;, in
<em>The Cambridge History of Moral Philosophy</em>, Sacha Golob and
Jens Timmermann (eds), Cambridge: Cambridge University Press,
535&ndash;548. doi:10.1017/9781139519267.042</li>

<li>Vander Veer, Garrett L., 1970, <em>Bradley&rsquo;s Metaphysics and
the Self</em>, New Haven, CT: Yale University Press.</li>

<li>Warnock, Mary, 1960, <em>Ethics since 1900</em>, first edition,
London/New York: Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>Wilson, Fred, 1999, &ldquo;The Significance for Psychology of
Bradley&rsquo;s Humean View of the Self&rdquo;, <em>Bradley
Studies</em>, 5(1): 5&ndash;44. doi:10.5840/bradley1999512</li>

<li>Wollheim, Richard, 1969, <em>F. H. Bradley</em>, Harmondsworth and
Baltimore: Penguin; fFirst published, 1959.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1993, <em>The Mind and Its Depths</em>,
Cambridge, MA: Harvard University Press.</li>

<li>Wright, Crispin, 1984, &ldquo;The Moral Organism?&rdquo;, in
Manser and Stock 1984: 77&ndash;97.</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="BiblMate">Bibliographical Material</h3>

<ul class="hanging">

<li>Ingardia, Richard, 1991, <em>Bradley: A Research
Bibliography</em>, (Bibliographies of Famous Philosophers), Bowling
Green, OH: Philosophy Documentation Center, Bowling Green State
University. Please note the volume contains occasional typos and
mistakes in the references, but to this date this is the most
comprehensive catalogue of literature on F.H. Bradley before 1991.
<!-- do not confuse with the earlier 1981 version --></li>
</ul>
</div> 

